Title: Suburbicon Official Trailer #1 (2017) Matt Damon, Oscar Isaac Crime Comedy HD
Comment:
This is an important movie. George Clooney does a fine job. One of Matt Damon's best. He is such a good person that to see him playing this terrible character is hard to believe. The worst scene is when he looks at the boarding schools brochures to send his son away to and tells his son he isn't doing a good enough job so he has to go "away". It is heartbreaking to know that these things were done to kids-they got sent away. The fear is real. Damon plays a deplorable character as does Ms. Moore. But the real movie is the rest of the story--the underlying theme of race separation and division that the Coen Brothers excel at. Telling many stories at once. Sadly, people tend now to cling to one side ot the other. This two party division is tearing apart our very Country. 
I have felt this way and experienced the actual fires (an actual lifetime of professional firings-deliberate sabotage-and out and out real fires that nearly killed me), the "pushing out"-and the otherness. I just want to belong. I think we all do. Regardless of our color, creed, or rough edges; we're all just people inside. I like the saying by the famous Astronomer Neill Degrasse Tyson, "My Race? -- is the Human Race." I hope we all get there. Someday. I wish the group that is hacking all my phones-every single phone- would stop doing it because it is awful. I think the Coen Brother's could make a fine film about our total loss of Privacy in today's online world--and how destructive this predatory means of hacking-recording and exploiting people's private real and online lives-can be. Just how destructive it is to the human psyche to be preyed upon day and night by unseen hackers. The damage these groups do is devastating. I really wish they would make that movie. I can't be the only one this is happening to. 
Best wishes to this fine cast and the amazing thought provoking Coen Brothers Brave Onwards üå†üèÜüçÄ~

Title: Suburbicon Official Trailer #1 (2017) Matt Damon, Oscar Isaac Crime Comedy HD
Comment: This movie was such a disappointment. It wasn't funny or intense like the trailer makes it look. The first half is too slow to actually get into the meat of the movie and is often disjointed and nonsensical, and in the second half, it's a mindless bloodbath. I'm not going to spoil anything major, but between the racism, the abundance of gore, and the behaviour/treatment of all of the characters, this movie somehow made me both legitimately bored yet uncomfortable to watch. The movie also ends very abruptly, without feeling very satisfying or interesting, despite the fucked up events that preceded it. I feel like it was supposed to convey a message of some sort, in the unexplained, unclear manner that some weird indie film would. In my opinion, save yourself the money and just torrent this movie or something. It's neither funny, nor insightful, nor a good thriller or horror movie. If Clooney hadn't directed it, this movie would not of made it to theathers.

Title: Suburbicon Official Trailer #1 (2017) Matt Damon, Oscar Isaac Crime Comedy HD
Comment:
Honestly one of the worst movies I've ever seen. The trailer is completely misleading and out of order with it's events, and the plot was awful.
Spoilers ahead.
1:04 - That was his uncle pulling the robber from underneath the bed, not his father. 
1:08 - The very end of the movie, where the father proceeds to threaten to kill his son and blame the already dead robber unless he keeps his mouth shut.
1:22 - That is not a robber, that's and insurance agent who called him out on his fraud.
1:27 - Said mobster never appears in the movie.
1:40 - Insurance agent discovering their fraud and trying to blackmail them.
1:51 - The people are rioting against an innocent black family, who completely irrelevant to the storyline.
1:54 - The Aunt is rolling the drugs to put in Nikki's sandwich and milk, so they would off him before he told anything to the police. The father eats said Sandwich and milk at 1:08.
2:06 - A firetruck rams into one of the actual mobsters and kills him.
2:07 - At the lineup, the officer turns on the lights.
2:08 - Nikki heard noises from the basement and thought the robbers had come back. It was his dad spanking his Aunt.
2:10 - Insurance agent mocking her.
2:12 - That was thrown in the black family's car.
 2:13 - Crashed firetruck.
At the very end, the child is the only one left, and has four bodies in his house. His uncle, his father, his aunt and the mobster. He proceeds to watch tv by his fathers corpse, then goes outside and plays ball with the neighbors child.

Comment:
‚ÄòSuburbicon‚Äô Review: George Clooney Delivers Racially Condescending, D-Level ‚ÄòFargo‚Äô
http://www.breitbart.com/big-hollywood/2017/10/27/suburbicon-review-george-clooney-delivers-racially-condescending-d-level-fargo/
by John Nolte           27 Oct 2017

In the mid-eighties, Joel and Ethan Coen came up with an idea and some ten years later, approached George Clooney with the screenplay. That project never happened. But Clooney was so enamored with it that he decided to rewrite (with producing partner Grant Heslov) the 30-year-old script and direct it himself. The result is Suburbicon and, due to its many failures, an all-new appreciation for the endlessly gifted brothers Coen.

Suburbicon is an inferior mash-up of the Coens‚Äô unforgettable 1996 Fargo and 2009‚Äôs somewhat forgettable A Serious Man. On one side, you have a blacker than black comedy of everyman Gardner Lodge (Matt Damon) committing an unspeakable crime. On the other, there is provincial Hollywood‚Äôs oft-stated certainty that only malevolence lurks beneath the perfectly trimmed lawns of post-war suburban America.

Clooney has the chunks required to make a great Coen brothers‚Äô film, beginning with their screenplay. Then there is the $25 million budget, Damon, Julianne Moore, Oscar Isaac, a never-ending supply of offbeat character actors, and Robert Elswit‚Äôs superb photography. Clooney assembled a pretty solid band. As a conductor, though, he lacks the chops to make anything resembling music.

Other than Isaac‚Äôs one superb scene as a sideways insurance investigator, none of the characters ever come close to popping to life. If you recall, despite all the awful things he was guilty of, one of the many genius elements in Fargo is that you still rooted for William H. Macy‚Äôs Jerry Lundegaard to get away with it. Even as you were horrified by his escalating behavior, the pathos, the rich emotional life within that character, kept you on his side.

Damon‚Äôs Lodge has no inner life. You feel no empathy towards him or towards Julianne Moore‚Äôs dual characters. They are only despicable, white bread gone bad. These are not characters; rather, they are logos for Clooney‚Äôs undying belief in his own superiority over such people. On top of a weak script and bad direction, Damon and Moore (and, therefore, the audience) are also the victims of the talent they lack to overcome both ‚Äî to broadcast our shared humanity without ever saying a word.

Another reason a Wisconsin boy like myself can love Fargo, which satirizes me and mine, is that beneath all the violence and funny accents, the Coens cannot hide their affection for us. And a real affection for their characters is always the difference between an A+ Coen experience (Blood Simple, Fargo, Miller‚Äôs Crossing, Raising Arizona, the grossly under-appreciated Man Who Wasn‚Äôt There, No Country for Old Men, True Grit) and a lesser Coen entry (Burn After Reading, Intolerable Cruelty, The Huduscker Proxy), which can come off as a bit smug.

This is primarily what so undoes Suburbicon. Clooney‚Äôs muse is his sanctimonious hatred for normal Americans, those he sees only as cancerous racists, marginally intelligent hypocrites, and vessels of quiet desperation ‚Äî you know, because deep down inside, we really all want to be like George.

If you care not a whit for the characters, even the villains, there is no tension. Suburbicon is utterly and completely tension-free. Even the little boy Nicky (a winning Noah Jupe) feels like a plot device, a cheap way to fabricate suspense by putting a child in danger. Clooney deserves credit for not making Nicky clever, a conjurer of unrealistic solutions, but the kid has no personality, and thanks to the trailer, we already know the outcome of the scene where we should be most worried about him.

As good as Oscar Issac is (in everything), screenwriter Clooney even bungles this. We are promised a character of consequence who will be around awhile. Then he is abruptly removed. Same with Jack Hightower‚Äôs policeman, who just never comes back. Gary Basaraba‚Äôs Uncle Mitch is wonderfully realized but has so little screen time, it leaves you annoyed as opposed to wanting more.

The well-constructed plot moves smoothly from scene to scene; you just do not care. Visual jabs at generic, fifties suburbia are everywhere; you have just seen them all before. The irony of the American dream permeates every scene, but this has been a tired trope since the credits rolled on 1999‚Äôs American Beauty.

On top of all that is an intrusive score and, worst of all, a racially condescending subplot that belongs in another movie. Based on a true story, a sorry chapter in American history, and Clooney‚Äôs transparent desperation to elevate his pulp into something meaningful and important, a black family makes the mistake of moving into Suburbicon. What starts off as shocked snobbery ends in a full-blown race riot.

The Meyers‚Äô story has two insurmountable problems. The first is that it never connects to the rest of the movie. Even thematically, unless you count white people suck, it just does not belong. Secondly, because Clooney‚Äôs racial attitudes are still ironically stuck in the fifties, his black characters are (mostly) silent and oh-so-noble sufferers ‚Äî tokens of Clooney‚Äôs woken enlightenment, limousine drivers of his pious liberalism, and, therefore, anything that might make them living, breathing people is pushed to the back of the bus.

Suburbicon is Clooney‚Äôs sixth directorial effort and fifth shot at screenwriting. How many swings does this guy get before his bubbled worshipers in Hollywood and the entertainment industry wake up to the fact that he is, at best, a mediocre talent? If the box office is any indicator, normal Americans caught on a decade ago ‚Äî which might explain why he hates us so.

*This article has been updated to correct the title of A Serious Man. 

Follow John Nolte on Twitter @NolteNC.

Nolte: After Defending Child Rapist Polanski, George Clooney Lectures Middle America in ‚ÄòSuburbicon‚Äô
by John Nolte               17 Oct 2017

Judging by the trailer and the early (and awful) Suburbicon reviews, George Clooney is once again chomping at the bit to lecture Middle America about just how awful and intolerant we all are. But are we really going to allow ourselves to be scolded by a mediocre director who defends an admitted child rapist like Roman Polanski?

At the time, back in February, the news that Clooney defended Polanski did not get much traction. The fugitive director was out of the spotlight and Clooney‚Äôs defense was made to the French tabloid Paris Match.

You see, Clooney was in France for the Cesars where he received an honorary award (probably because nothing he makes deserves an award-award). While accepting it in front of the fawning European press, Clooney naturally used the opportunity to trash President Trump and lecture the world about what is right and wrong.

‚ÄúAs citizens of the world, we‚Äôre going to have to work harder and harder not to let hate win ‚Ä¶ We cannot defend freedom abroad by deserting it at home ‚Ä¶ Love Trumps hate, courage Trumps fear and always rights Trump‚Äôs wrongs,‚Äù he said bravely, to those who agreed with him 100 percent.

Oddly enough, though, Mr. Right-and-Wrong has a warped set of moral  values when it comes to the issue of fugitive child rapists. Because what Clooney sees as wrong  in the case of Polanski, is the pursuit of long overdue justice.

What else are we to assume when Clooney says of Polanski: [emphasis added]

    ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know enough about the Polanski affair to talk about it in detail. But what I understand is that he had an agreement with a judge and that the judge didn‚Äôt respect. I also know that the victim now supports him.‚Äù And he concluded: ‚ÄúWhen you think about all that this 83-year-old man has been through, it‚Äôs awful to imagine that they‚Äôre still after him.‚Äù

Yes, ‚Äúit‚Äôs awful to imagine‚Äù because of all that Poor Roman ‚Äúhas been through.‚Äù

In 1977, Polanski admitted to raping a 13 year-old girl (who also says she was sodomized). Before he could be sentenced, Polanski fled America for Europe where, for the last 40 years, a who‚Äôs-who of the world‚Äôs elite have celebrated and enabled his lavish fugitive lifestyle.

During those terrible, awful decades, poor Polanski has ‚Äúbeen through‚Äù the winning of an Academy Award (and standing ovation) from Hollywood, has directed more than a dozen films, has been feted and worshiped in most every European capital that does not extradite, and has made millions of dollars.

Polanski is the cream of the international film world‚Äôs crop and because he cannot come to Hollywood, Hollywood comes to him.

Oh, and something else that Poor Polanski has ‚Äúbeen through‚Äù ‚Äî allegations from three other women who claim he sexually assaulted them as minors.

Last week, Clooney said he knew nothing! about the 20 years of allegations surrounding his colleague Harvey Weinstein. Even though Ashley Judd, Colin Firth, Rose McGowan, and Courtney Love had heard the rumors, Clooney was totally out of that loop.

Even if you believe that, it begs a question: if Clooney opposes seeing a fugitive child rapist face justice, are we also supposed to believe that someone who is that morally illiterate would have done the right thing had he known about Weinstein?

Anyway, coming soon to a theater near you, George Leave-The-Child-Rapist-Alone Clooney will lecture the rest of us about right and wrong.

The suburbs might not be perfect, but the only people I know of who defend child rapists are in Harveywood.

Hey, before I go, how about a thought experiment‚Ä¶

Try to imagine just how much better off leftwing Hollywood would be right now if they despised sexual predators and child rapists half as much as they do us normal Americans.
